			<div class="text" id="comment-73015287048">

				<strong class="title">General Comment</strong>There is one thing that surprisingly no one has even hinted at.  This song was written in '74, what was the one thing that all of America was going through at that time? The Vietnam War.  The lyrics clearly are about the Vietnam War.  Every verse indicates war, death and Vietnam.<br />
<br />
First Verse: 'Twas in another lifetime (soldier's life), one of toil and blood (killing and bloodshed)<br />
When blackness was a virtue (Vietnamese used darkness to fight) and the road was full of mud (dirt roads + lots of rain = muddy roads)<br />
I came in from the wilderness (Vietnamese jungles), a creature void of form (stranger to Vietnamese people).<br />
<br />
Second Verse:  In a world of steel-eyed death (guns), and men who are fighting to be warm (warmth = safety, fighting to be safe).<br />
<br />
Third Verse:  Not a word was spoke between us (different languages), there was little risk involved (villagers not armed)<br />
Everything up to that point had been left unresolved (war was still raging around them).<br />
Try imagining a place where it's always safe and warm (soldierâs often imagined things and people from home to keep them going).<br />
<br />
Fourth Verse:  I was burned out from exhaustion, buried in the hail,<br />
Poisoned in the bushes an' blown out on the trail,<br />
Hunted like a crocodile, ravaged in the corn.  (Burned, buried, poisoned, blown out, hunted, ravaged; all these words are describing war and fighting)<br />
<br />
Fifth Verse:  Suddenly I turned around and she was standin' there (saw a person in the Vietnamese, just like in America)<br />
With silver bracelets on her wrists and flowers in her hair (hippie movement in America).<br />
She walked up to me so gracefully (donât forget the terrible Kent State shooting in â70, Allison Krause said that âflowers are better than guns,â as she place a flower in a guradsmens rifel barrel) and took my crown of thorns (in â72 Don McLean wrote a song, American Pie, âtook my crown of thornsâ is clearly a line from this famous song. âThe jester stole his thorny crown,â in American Pie, the jester has been interpreted as Dylan taking the crown from âThe King of rock and roll,â Elvis).<br />
<br />
Sixth Verse:  Now there's a wall between us (Vietnamese villages were walled off to protect from NVA invasion), somethin' there's been lost (American troops dropping agent orange all over the Vietnamese jungles killed and maimed many innocent villagers turning them against us)<br />
I took too much for granted (Americans had a mentality that they WOULD win the war because âweâre America and the greatestâ), got my signals crossed.<br />
Just to think that it all began on a long-forgotten morn (LBJ falsely started the Vietnam War under the pretenses that the USS Maddox was attacked at 3 am on August 2, 1964).<br />
<br />
Seventh Verse:  Well, the deputy walks on hard nails (LBJ was under pressure from Americans to withdraw from the war for years before he actually did) and the preacher rides a mount (MLK is dead, he can no longer preach about peace and love)<br />
But nothing really matters much, it's doom alone that counts (a scoreboard was actually kept in this time counting Vietnamese deaths to our own deaths)<br />
And the one-eyed undertaker (guns), he blows a futile horn (a useless attempt at winning an un-winnable war).<br />
<br />
Eighth Verse: I've heard newborn babies wailin' like a mournin' dove (agent orange was dumped over many Vietnamese villages killing and burning everyone)<br />
And old men with broken teeth stranded without love (made widowers as family was killed in raids and from agent orange).<br />
Do I understand your question, man, is it hopeless and forlorn (man soldierâs asked why they were fighting an unending war)?<br />
<br />
Ninth Verse:  In a little hilltop village, they gambled for my clothes (NVA soldierâs would strip clothes, weapons and ammunition off dead American soldiers if they were left in the field)<br />
I bargained for salvation (many soldiers bargained for Vietnamese items) an' they gave me a lethal dose (one of the biggest trades was for pot, what the soldierâs didnât know was that it was usually laced with red rock heroin).<br />
I offered up my Innocence and got repaid with scorn.<br />
<br />
Tenth Verse:  Well, I'm livin' in a foreign country (Vietnam) but I'm bound to cross the line (by international law, we were not allowed to leave S. Vietnam; regardless, we made bombing expeditions in Laos, Cambodia and N. Vietnam)<br />
Beauty walks a razor's edge (beauty = life, opposite of life = death; there is a thin line between life and death in war), someday I'll make it mine (in war, soldierâs kill supposedly without feeling, but humans are not designed to see death, so it is natural to want to do something after the war to want to give back life, to restore beauty).<br />
If I could only turn back the clock to when God and her were born (Dylan wishes he could turn back time to prevent this terrible war).<br />
<br />
"Come in," she said,<br />
"I'll give you shelter from the storm." (These lines run through every verse.  If, shelter = protection and storm = war, then the title of the song means âprotection from the war,â something every soldier in Vietnam wanted)				
